# Course Naming Convention

## Overview

This project uses a consistent course naming convention that separates user-facing display names from internal identifiers (course numbers and Canvas IDs).

## Official Course Data Source

All course information is stored in `_data/courses.yaml`. This file is the **single source of truth** for:
- Course display names
- Course numbers (e.g., CS-6343)
- Canvas course IDs
- Semester information
- Course descriptions
- Syllabus and media links

## Naming Rules

### User-Facing Content (Blog Titles, Page Headers, Navigation)

**DO NOT include course numbers in:**
- Blog post titles
- Page headers
- Navigation menus
- Course section headings
- User-visible text

**CORRECT:**
- "Cryptography – Introduction to Symmetric Encryption"
- "Software Verification and Validation – Testing Strategies"
- "Logic for Computer Scientists – Propositional Logic Basics"

**INCORRECT:**
- "CS-6343 Cryptography – Introduction to Symmetric Encryption"
- "CS-5374 Software Verification and Validation – Testing Strategies"

### Internal/Agent Use Only

Course numbers and Canvas IDs should **ONLY** be used by:
- Agents for Canvas LMS MCP lookups
- Internal scripts and automation
- Data files and configuration
- Front matter `course_id` or `canvas_id` fields

### Front Matter Convention

When creating blog posts or pages related to courses:

```yaml
---
title: "Introduction to Symmetric Encryption"  # NO course number
course: "Cryptography"                          # Display name only
course_slug: "cryptography"                     # For URL/filtering
# Internal fields (agent use only):
# canvas_id: 70714
# course_number: "CS-6343"
---
```

### Course Display Names (Reference)

Always use these exact display names in user-facing content:

| Display Name | Course Number | Slug |
|--------------|---------------|------|
| Cryptography | CS-6343 | cryptography |
| Software Verification and Validation | CS-5374 | software-verification |
| Intelligent Systems | CS-5368 | intelligent-systems |
| Logic for Computer Scientists | CS-5384 | logic-for-computer-scientists |
| Theory of Automata | CS-5383 | theory-of-automata |
| Analysis of Algorithms | CS-5381 | analysis-of-algorithms |
| Software Project Management | CS-5363 | software-project-management |
| Machine Learning Security | CS-5331 | machine-learning-security |
| General | - | general |

### Referencing Course Data in Jekyll

```liquid
{% comment %} Lookup course by slug {% endcomment %}
{% assign course = site.data.courses | where: "slug", "cryptography" | first %}
{{ course.display_name }}
{{ course.description }}

{% comment %} Iterate all courses {% endcomment %}
{% for course in site.data.courses %}
  {{ course.display_name }} ({{ course.semester }})
{% endfor %}
```

## Migration Notes

When updating existing content:
1. Remove course numbers from titles (e.g., "CS-6343" from "CS-6343 Cryptography")
2. Use `course: "Cryptography"` instead of `course: "CS-6343 Cryptography"` in front matter
3. Update any hardcoded course lists to reference `site.data.courses`

## Canvas LMS Integration

When agents need to lookup course information via canvas-lms-mcp:
1. Reference `_data/courses.yaml` for the `canvas_id`
2. Use the canvas_id for API calls
3. Never expose the canvas_id in user-facing content
